Network Traffic Classification and Anomaly Detection

Problem Statement

Modern enterprise networks handle massive volumes of traffic from varied applications and protocols. However, distinguishing between normal and anomalous network behavior, or recognizing the specific application behind a flow, remains a challenging taskespecially when done manually or with outdated rules.

You, as a Data Scientist, are tasked with building a machine learning classification model that can learn from historical packet-level data and classify the type of network protocol being used (e.g., ARP, RARP, NBNS). This model should also help in identifying unusual or potentially malicious traffic, providing critical insights for anomaly detection and cybersecurity monitoring.

Business Context

The data was collected in a controlled lab setting at the University of Cincinnati using Wireshark. With over 394,000 instances of real packet-level traffic observed over the span of one hour, this dataset mimics a real-world enterprise network scenario.

This kind of analysis is vital for:

  • Network Intrusion Detection (NIDS) spotting potential breaches or malicious activity.
  • Traffic Classification identifying which applications generate what type of traffic.
  • Anomaly Detection discovering irregular patterns in volume, protocol use, or communication flow.
  • Performance Monitoring understanding which traffic is legitimate or problematic and optimizing flow.

Project Objective

Develop a classification model that predicts the network protocol for a given packet using attributes such as source, destination, packet size, and timestamp. This model will support both:

  • Protocol Identification (e.g., ARP, NBNS)
  • Foundations for anomaly and intrusion detection systems (IDS)

Data Description

Feature Name Description
No Sequential number of the packet (instance ID)
Timestamp Time at which the packet was captured
Source Source IP address or MAC (sender of packet)
Destination Destination IP or MAC (receiver of packet)
Protocol Type of network protocol used (e.g., ARP, NBNS, RARP)
Length Size of the packet in bytes
Info Human-readable description of the packet content (e.g., ARP request detail)

Why This Dataset Is Valuable

  • Real Network Scenario: Captured from public, private, and enterprise networks.
  • Multiple Use Cases: Traffic classification, performance monitoring, anomaly detection, and intrusion detection.
  • Rich Volume: 394,137 rows large enough to train deep or ensemble models.
  • Open Domain: Licensed as CC0 (public domain), so usable for research and deployment.

Possible Machine Learning Applications

  1. Traffic Classification: Identify traffic types based on packet features.
  2. Anomaly Detection: Flag rare or unusual patterns as suspicious (baseline modeling).
  3. Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS): Learn typical patterns and flag DoS/malicious behaviors.

Data Availability & Acknowledgment:

This dataset was obtained from Kaggle, where it was shared by Ravikumar Gattu. We gratefully acknowledge the author's contribution. The dataset is freely available under a permissive license, making it suitable for academic and applied machine learning projects.

Ref: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ravikumargattu/network-traffic-dataset/data

Part A: Stating and Refining the Question

Research Question: "Can we classify network traffic protocols (e.g., NBNS, ARP) based on packet features like Time, Source, Destination, and Length?" Why this question? Intrusion detection and network monitoring systems need to understand the nature of traffic.

Classifying protocol types helps in understanding typical vs. suspicious patterns.

    • This column is likely redundant for modeling and can be dropped.

  2. Timestamped Traffic:

    • The Time column represents the timestamp (in seconds) since the start of capture.
    • The values increase gradually, confirming sequential recording of network packets.

  3. Source and Destination Format:

    • The Source and Destination fields contain IP addresses (e.g., 192.167.8.166) or MAC-like device identifiers (e.g., VMware_8a:5c:e6, Broadcast).
    • These will need to be encoded for modeling since they are categorical.

  4. Protocol Variety:

    • Two protocol types are visible: NBNS and ARP.
    • These will serve as the target classes for the classification model.

  5. Packet Lengths:

    • Length values range from 60 to 92 in these initial rows.
    • This feature appears to be numeric and informative could impact classification.

  6. Info Column:

    • Contains textual descriptions of the packet content (e.g., "Who has 192.167.7.175? Tell 192.167.0.1").
    • Useful for interpretation and manual inspection but not directly usable for initial modeling unless processed via NLP.

Observations:

Time Column (e.g., duration, timestamp)

  • Lots of Data: We have a large number of recorded times: 394,136 entries.
  • Average Time: The typical time observed is around 781.60.
  • Spread: Times vary a fair bit, with a standard deviation of 263.60. This means they aren't all clustered tightly around the average.
  • Range: The shortest recorded time is 0.00, and the longest is 1256.92. The 0.00 might need a quick check to see if it's expected (like a start point) or an anomaly.
  • Evenly Spread (Mostly): The median (middle value) is 781.93, which is very close to the average. This suggests that the 'Time' values are fairly evenly distributed without a strong bias towards very high or very low values.

Length Column (e.g., packet size, data volume)

  • Lots of Data (Again): Like 'Time', you have 394,136 entries for 'Length'.
  • Average Length: The average length is about 985.58.
  • Very Spread Out: The 'Length' values are highly variable, with a standard deviation of 837.37. This is a large number compared to the average, indicating a wide range of different lengths.
  • Huge Range: Lengths go from a small 42.00 up to a massive 49,745.00. This huge maximum suggests there are some exceptionally large data units in your network.
  • Skewed Data (Lots of Small, Few Large): The median (middle value) for 'Length' is 1462.00, which is noticeably higher than the average (985.58). This is a crucial point! It means that most of your lengths are actually smaller than the average. The average is pulled up by a few very large lengths (like those big packets or data transfers). This kind of distribution is called right-skewed [Image of right skewed distribution].

What This Tells us Overall

  • data consistently measures both time and length for the same large set of network events.
  • While 'Time' seems fairly consistent, 'Length' is much more unpredictable.
  • The 'Length' data has a significant number of small values but also contains some extremely large values. These large values are important to note as they significantly impact the overall average and could represent specific types of network traffic, large file transfers, or even unusual events.

# --- 1. Convert 'Time' Column to Datetime (Relative) and Extract Features ---
# Assume 'Time' is seconds since some start. pandas' to_datetime can handle this as epoch.
# Since the values are small floats, it's likely seconds.
# We'll treat 0.0 as the epoch for relative time.
df['Time_Original_Seconds'] = df['Time'] # Keep original for reference if needed
df['Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Time'], unit='s', origin='unix')
In[12]:
# Extract time-based features (relative to the start of the capture, not actual 1970 calendar)
# These features will show patterns within the captured duration.
df['Time_Elapsed_Seconds'] = (df['Time'] - df['Time'].min()).dt.total_seconds()
df['Hour_of_Capture'] = df['Time'].dt.hour
df['Minute_of_Capture'] = df['Time'].dt.minute
df['Second_of_Capture'] = df['Time'].dt.second
df['Microsecond_of_Capture'] = df['Time'].dt.microsecond

Observations:

The Distribution of Time_Elapsed_Seconds histogram shows a multi-modal distribution, indicating several distinct periods of high activity within the captured duration.

  • There's an initial sharp peak around 500 seconds, followed by another significant peak near 800 seconds, and several smaller peaks throughout the range. This suggests bursts of events or distinct phases in the data collection.
  • The frequency generally remains high between approximately 400 and 1250 seconds, with varying peaks and troughs.

The Box Plot of Time_Elapsed_Seconds complements the histogram by summarizing the central tendency and spread.

  • The median (the line inside the box) is around 780 seconds, which aligns with one of the prominent peaks in the histogram.
  • The interquartile range (IQR), represented by the box, spans roughly from 550 seconds to 980 seconds, indicating that 50% of the events occurred within this window.
  • There are outliers on both the lower and higher ends, but they are not extremely far from the main body of the data, especially on the lower end. The left whisker extends very close to 0, implying some events occur almost immediately at the start of the capture. The right whisker extends to around 1250 seconds, with some individual points extending further, indicating the full range of the capture.

Observations on Length

The Distribution of Length histogram is highly right-skewed, with a massive concentration of values at the lower end of the length spectrum.

  • There's an extremely high frequency of very small lengths, peaking sharply near 0. This suggests that the majority of packets or data units are very small.
  • The frequency drops off dramatically as length increases, with very few occurrences beyond a few thousand.

The Box Plot of Length clearly highlights the skewness and the presence of numerous outliers.

  • The median is very close to 0, and the entire box (IQR) is compressed at the lower end, reinforcing that most data points have small lengths.
  • There are a large number of individual points extending far to the right, indicating significant outliers with much larger lengths. These outliers are spread out from roughly 5,000 up to 50,000, suggesting that while most data units are small, there are occasional large ones. This is common in network data where small control packets are frequent, but large data transfers (e.g., file downloads) also occur.

EDA Summary Report: Network Traffic Analysis

1. Data Overview & Quality

The dataset contains approximately 394,125 network traffic records.

  • Duplicates: The presence of 11 duplicate rows indicates a minor data quality issue that was addressed by removal.
  • Time Data: The Time column, initially appearing as Unix epoch, was correctly converted and treated as elapsed seconds from the start of the capture. This allowed for the extraction of relative time-based features (Time_Elapsed_Seconds, Minute_of_Capture, Second_of_Capture). The Hour_of_Capture feature was found to be uniform (all '0'), indicating the entire capture spanned less than one hour.

2. Univariate Analysis Key Findings

  • Time_Elapsed_Seconds: The capture duration is approximately 1250 seconds (just over 20 minutes). The distribution is multi-modal, showing several distinct bursts of activity throughout the capture, with major peaks around 500 and 800 seconds.
  • Length: This feature is highly right-skewed, with the vast majority of packets having very small lengths. However, there are numerous significant outliers representing much larger packets (up to 50,000), which likely correspond to large data transfers.
  • Source & Destination: Both columns exhibit extreme imbalance, with one IP address, 192.167.7.162, being overwhelmingly dominant as both a source (over 120,000 events) and an even more dominant destination (over 275,000 events). This strongly suggests 192.167.7.162 is a central hub, server, or the main point of data collection/observation in the network.
  • Protocol: TCP is the most dominant protocol, accounting for the vast majority of traffic. TLSv1.3 is the second most frequent, highlighting the prevalence of encrypted communication. Other protocols are much less frequent.
  • Minute_of_Capture & Second_of_Capture: While Hour_of_Capture showed no variation, these features revealed that activity is not uniform within the minutes and seconds of the capture. Specific minutes (e.g., 8, 13, 20) and seconds (e.g., 4, 21, 25) had higher event frequencies, indicating fine-grained temporal clustering of network events.

3. Bivariate Analysis & Target Variable (Is_Suspected_Traffic) Findings

A new binary target variable, Is_Suspected_Traffic, was created based on a predefined list of "suspected" protocols (e.g., NBNS, ARP, SSLv2).

  • Length vs. Is_Suspected_Traffic: This is a strong differentiator.
    • Suspected traffic predominantly consists of small packets with a very tight length distribution.
    • Normal traffic has a much wider range of lengths, including many very large packets, indicating diverse data transfer activities. This is a key finding for identifying suspected vs. normal activity.
  • Time_Elapsed_Seconds vs. Is_Suspected_Traffic: While both normal and suspected traffic occur throughout the capture, suspected traffic tends to have a slightly lower median elapsed time and broader spread in its central distribution, suggesting it might be more prevalent earlier in the capture or more evenly distributed over time.
  • Microsecond_of_Capture vs. Is_Suspected_Traffic: No significant difference was observed at this very fine-grained temporal level; both types of traffic occur similarly across microsecond intervals.
  • Source & Destination vs. Is_Suspected_Traffic:
    • The most dominant Source and Destination IP (192.167.7.162) are overwhelmingly associated with Normal traffic.
    • This implies that suspected traffic is either generated/received by less frequent IPs not among the top communicators, or makes up an extremely small proportion of the traffic from dominant IPs.
  • Protocol vs. Is_Suspected_Traffic: The analysis confirmed the direct relationship between the defined suspected protocols and the Is_Suspected_Traffic flag. Protocols like TCP are exclusively normal, while ARP, NBNS, SSLv2, etc., are exclusively suspected.

Final Findings & Recommendations

  1. Packet Length is a Primary Indicator: The Length of a packet is a highly effective feature for distinguishing between normal and suspected network traffic, with suspected traffic almost always being small.
  2. Temporal Patterns Exist, but are Subtle for Suspicion: While the network exhibits clear temporal patterns of activity (bursts at specific seconds/minutes), these temporal features are not strong direct indicators of suspected traffic on their own at a macro level (hours/minutes/seconds). The timing of suspected traffic seems broadly distributed rather than clustered.
  3. Dominant IPs are Primarily "Clean": The most active Source and Destination in the network are associated almost entirely with normal traffic. This suggests that the core communication within the network is largely legitimate. If suspected traffic exists, it's either from less frequent/peripheral devices or constitutes a very small proportion of the dominant IPs' overall communication.
  4. Protocol-based Classification is Effective: The creation of Is_Suspected_Traffic based on Protocol is a clear and direct way to segment the data for further analysis. This highlights the importance of the Protocol field itself as a direct classification feature.

Next Steps for Further Analysis:

  • Focus on the "Small" Length Traffic: Investigate the characteristics of all small packets, especially those not classified as "suspected" by protocol, to see if they hold hidden patterns of concern.
  • Investigate Less Frequent Sources/Destinations: Analyze the Source and Destination IPs that are not among the top communicators, as these might be the primary actors in suspected activities.
  • Temporal Correlation with Suspected Traffic: While no strong direct correlation was observed, it would be valuable to look for sequential patterns do suspected events tend to follow or precede specific normal events? This would require time-series analysis beyond simple bivariate plots.
  • Feature Engineering: Consider creating new features like Packet_Rate_Per_Second or Bytes_Per_Second to capture dynamic aspects of traffic flow.
  • Anomaly Detection: Given the nature of the target variable (created as a proxy for 'suspicion'), this dataset is well-suited for unsupervised anomaly detection techniques, where patterns of "normal" behavior are learned, and deviations are flagged as potential anomalies.

# 2. Outlier detection and handling for 'Length' and 'Time'
def detect_and_clip_outliers(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    df[column] = df[column].clip(lower=lower_bound, upper=upper_bound)
    return df

Model Building

Model Evaluation Criterion

Objective:

The primary goal of this machine learning project is to build a classification model that accurately identifies suspicious network traffic from normal traffic using flow-level data captured via Wireshark.

Nature of Predictions:

Lets define the meaning of classification outcomes in the context of anomaly detection in network traffic:

  • True Positives (TP): Suspicious (anomalous/malicious) network traffic correctly predicted as suspicious.
  • False Negatives (FN): Suspicious network traffic wrongly predicted as normal i.e., the model missed an attack.
  • False Positives (FP): Normal network traffic wrongly predicted as suspicious i.e., the model raised a false alarm.
  • True Negatives (TN): Normal traffic correctly predicted as normal.

Which Metric to Optimize?

In cybersecurity and anomaly detection:

  • False Negatives (FN) are the most dangerous because an undetected malicious packet can compromise the network.
  • False Positives (FP) are acceptable to some extent, as they can be filtered by human review or further analysis.

Therefore, Recall becomes the most important metric.

Why Recall?

  • Recall = TP / (TP + FN)
  • It measures the model's ability to catch all suspicious traffic.
  • A high Recall means fewer false negatives, i.e., the model successfully flags most of the dangerous or malicious packets.

Business Impact

Failing to identify suspicious traffic can lead to:

  • Intrusion into the network
  • Data leaks
  • Denial of Service (DoS) attacks
  • System compromise and loss of trust

In contrast, falsely flagging a normal packet (FP) leads to:

  • Temporary overhead
  • Manual verification

Thus, false negatives are much more costly than false positives, making Recall our key metric.

Evaluation Metric

We will evaluate the model using multiple metrics:

  • Accuracy: Overall correctness
  • Precision: Proportion of detected anomalies that are actually anomalies
  • Recall ( Key Metric): Proportion of actual anomalies that were detected
  • F1-Score: Harmonic mean of precision and recall
  • Confusion Matrix: Detailed breakdown of prediction types

Summary

Metric Focus Why Important?
Recall Primary To reduce false negatives (missed attacks)
Precision Secondary To avoid too many false alarms
Accuracy Tertiary May be misleading with class imbalance
F1 Score Balanced When both Precision and Recall matter
In[165]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target, pos_label='positive'):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    pos_label: the positive label to be considered for metrics computation
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, pos_label=pos_label)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, pos_label=pos_label)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, pos_label=pos_label)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1
        },
        index=[0]
    )

    return df_perf
In[166]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

HyperparameterTuning

Sample Parameter Grids

Note

Sample parameter grids have been provided to do necessary hyperparameter tuning. These sample grids are expected to provide a balance between model performance improvement and execution time. One can extend/reduce the parameter grid based on execution time and system configuration.

  • Please note that if the parameter grid is extended to improve the model performance further, the execution time will increase

  • For Gradient Boosting:

    • param_grid = { "init": [AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1),DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)], "n_estimators": np.arange(50,110,25), "learning_rate": [0.01,0.1,0.05], "subsample":[0.7,0.9], "max_features":[0.5,0.7,1], }

  • For Adaboost:

    • param_grid = { "n_estimators": np.arange(50,110,25), "learning_rate": [0.01,0.1,0.05], "base_estimator": [ DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1), DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, random_state=1), ], }

  • For Bagging Classifier:

    • param_grid = { 'max_samples': [0.8,0.9,1], 'max_features': [0.7,0.8,0.9], 'n_estimators' : [30,50,70], }

  • For Random Forest:

    • param_grid = { "n_estimators": [50,110,25], "min_samples_leaf": np.arange(1, 4), "max_features": [np.arange(0.3, 0.6, 0.1),'sqrt'], "max_samples": np.arange(0.4, 0.7, 0.1) }

  • For Decision Trees:

    • param_grid ={ 'max_depth': np.arange(2,6), 'min_samples_leaf': [1, 4, 7], 'max_leaf_nodes' : [10, 15], 'min_impurity_decrease': [0.0001,0.001] }

  • For XGBoost (optional):

    • param_grid={'n_estimators':np.arange(50,110,25), 'scale_pos_weight':[1,2,5], 'learning_rate':[0.01,0.1,0.05], 'gamma':[1,3], 'subsample':[0.7,0.9] }

Business Insights and Conclusions

1. Key Business Insights from EDA

  • Network Hub Identified: A single IP address (192.167.7.162) accounts for the majority of network traffic. It acts as a central nodelikely a key server or logging device. Importantly, this IP is almost entirely associated with normal traffic, suggesting core infrastructure is secure and stable.

  • Suspicious Traffic Is Isolated: Suspicious traffic is not coming from or targeting the main IPs, indicating that less frequent or peripheral IPs may pose greater risk and need deeper investigation.

  • Packet Length Is a Strong Security Indicator: The Length feature is the top signal for identifying suspicious activity. Suspected packets tend to be small and tightly clustered in size, whereas normal packets show diverse lengths including large data transfers.

  • Protocol Type Is Directly Tied to Suspicion: Protocols such as NBNS, ARP, RARP, SSLv2, and ICMP were strongly associated with suspicious activity. In contrast, TCP and TLSv1.3 were linked to normal traffic. This makes protocol filtering a valuable early defense mechanism.

  • Burst Traffic Patterns Exist: While suspected traffic is not tightly clustered in time, the entire network shows temporal activity bursts (e.g., around 500 and 800 seconds). These spikes might represent windows of opportunity or vulnerability.

2. Insights from Machine Learning Modeling

  • High Model Accuracy: All top models performed exceptionally well, but Random Forest trained with oversampled data had the best overall balance:

    • Accuracy: 89.7%
    • Recall: 94.5% (highly effective in detecting all suspicious cases)
    • Precision: 89.1% (low false positives)
    • F1 Score: 91.7% (strong overall balance)

  • Recall vs Precision Trade-Off:

    • AdaBoost and Gradient Boosting models had slightly higher recall (96.6%) but lower precision (83%), meaning they may produce more false alarms.
    • Random Forest maintained high precision while still keeping recall above 94%, making it a more balanced and production-ready model.

  • Oversampling Works Best: Models trained on oversampled data consistently outperformed those trained on undersampled data, indicating that oversampling is the preferred approach for handling class imbalance in this context.

3. Final Model Recommendation

Selected Model: Random Forest trained with Oversampled Data

Justification:

  • Best F1 score (91.7%) across all models.
  • Highest precision (89.1%) ensures that flagged traffic is truly suspicious, reducing false positives and alert fatigue.
  • Excellent generalization to unseen data, as validation and test performance are nearly identical.
  • Easy to interpret and fast to deploy in real-time monitoring systems.

4. Business Recommendations

  • Deploy the Random Forest model as a core module in your network monitoring system to flag potentially suspicious traffic in real time.

  • Set up monitoring for low-frequency IPs: Since dominant IPs are largely clean, focus attention and alert thresholds on peripheral or rarely seen IPs.

  • Implement protocol-based filtering as a baseline rule: Block or sandbox traffic using rare protocols like NBNS, SSLv2, ARP unless explicitly needed.

  • Establish alerts for small packet bursts, especially outside business hours, as these are statistically tied to anomalous behavior.

  • Combine ML predictions with rule-based heuristics (like length < 100 and protocol in [NBNS, ARP]) to enhance security monitoring.

  • Regularly retrain models as new traffic behaviors emerge, especially with changing protocol usage or evolving threats.
